ACCESSOR BINDINGS

All tabular accessors must use wildcard notation for column-oriented data extraction.

Converting keyFields to column accessors:

JSON data (array-of-objects or object-of-objects):
- keyFields contain paths like `$.users[0].name` or `$.data.items[0].price`
- Convert to wildcard accessor: replace specific index with `[*]`
- Example: `$.users[0].name` → `$[*].name`
- Example: `$.data.items[0].price` → `$[*].price`
- Nested paths: `$.company.employees[0].profile.email` → `$[*].profile.email`

CSV data (array-of-arrays or object-of-arrays):
- keyFields already use `$[*][N]` notation
- Use directly without modification
- Example: `$[*][0]`, `$[*][1]`, `$[*][2]`

Object keys column:
- To access object property names, use tilde operator: `$[*]~`
- Example: for `{user_123: {...}, user_456: {...}}` → accessor `$[*]~` extracts keys

Role heuristics for accessor_bindings:
- String fields → roles: ["label"]
- Number fields → roles: ["value"]
- Enum/categorical fields → roles: ["categorical"]
- Object keys → roles: ["identifier"]

